frameDefinitions: An Agent has done or omitted to do an Act or is responsible for the obtaining of a State_of_affairs, which a Judge deems to constitute a violation of an obligation or a moral guideline.

This frame involves a static (primarily spatial) relationship between a Location and a Theme, in which the Theme is located in many or all subregions of the Location, and is thus construable as covering it.
A Figure is located adjacent to a Ground.
This frame contains nouns denoting Aggregates of Individuals.
A group of Individuals form a group, the Entourage, which remains co-located with the Attended_person.
frameExamples: Kim failed to fully <t>justify</t> his decision.
The hand <t>around</t> the sword-hilt was no less impressive than the sword .
The two houses were <t>adjacent</t> , so she bought them together .
An <t><fex name='Agg'>army</fex></t> of postal workers descended on my office.
Just before eleven o'clock, one of the consultants came to do a ward round, followed by his <t><fex name='ent'>entourage</fex></t> of junior doctors and medical students.
listRoleDefinitions: The person or organization that  is held responsible for a prior <fen>Act</fen> or for a <fen>State_of_affairs</fen>.
An action  for which the <fen>Agent</fen> is held responsible, frequently one that the <fen>Agent</fen> has taken themself.
A <fen>State_of_affairs</fen> that the Agent is held responsible for.
The <fen>Time</fen> of the justifying event.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is the entity located with respect to the <fen>Ground</fen>.
The <fen>Ground</fen> is the area that the <fen>Figure</fen> surrounds.
The area or zone immediately external to the <fen>Ground</fen>.  This role excludes <fen>Figure</fen> and is only used in particular constructions such as the following:
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Figure</fen> is located around the <fen>Ground</fen>.

The <fen>Theme</fen> in this frame is the object which is described as standing in some spatial relation to a particular <fen>Location</fen>.  <fen>Theme</fen> typically occurs as the External Argument or, with passives, as a PP Complement headed by 'with' or 'by'.
<fen>Location</fen> is the entity or area with respect to which the <fen>Theme</fen>'s spatial arrangement is described.  This frame element generally occurs as an NP Object.
The time at which the <fen>Theme</fen> occupies the <fen>Location</fen>.
The <fen>Ground</fen> serves as a basis for describing the location of the <fen>Figure</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is perceived as located relative to a certain <fen>Ground</fen> location. The figure can be an entity or an event.
The <fen>Figures</fen> are items which mutually serve to identify the location of the other items.
The period of time during which the locative relation between <fen>Figure</fen> and <fen>Ground</fen> obtains.
This role identifies the people or things that form  the <fen>Aggregate</fen>.
This role identifies the collection of entities that are the <fen>Aggregate</fen>.
This role identifies the people or things that form  the <fen>Entourage</fen>.
This role identifies the collection of entities that follow the Attended.
The <fen>Attended_person</fen> is followed by the <fen>Entourage</fen>.

Kim failed  to fully justify <fex>his decision</fex>.
The lawyers tried  to justify <fex>enormous punitive damages being paid to victims on a first-past-the-post system</fex> .
He had <fex>both hands</fex> wrapped around her arm .
The cat is adjacent <fex>to the mat</fex>.
<fex>The cat</fex> is adjacent to the mat.
A crowd <fex>of hoodlums</fex> filled the plaza.
A <fex><t>crowd</t></fex> of hoodlums filled the plaza.
Just before eleven o'clock, one of the consultants came to do a ward round, followed by his entourage <fex>of junior doctors and medical students</fex>.
Most of the large <fex><t>entourage</t></fex> the president had brought with him quietly left him.
<fex>The lord's</fex> train consisted of several dozen servants, cooks, and other attendants.
